  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Weather and Climate Science for Service Partnership Southeast Asia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Collaborative project between Partners in the Southeast Asia Region and UK.  A regional approach to the &#x2018;maritime continent&#x2019; to  maximise the value and impact to help improve modelling capability of high impact weather in the region, enabling mitigation of risk from extreme weather events.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This aims to jointly develop and improve underpinning capability in global and regional forecasting systems, and advance the understanding of high-impact weather events in order to provide better advice and mitigate their socio-economic impacts. WCSSP Southeast Asia is a regional project currently involving three partner countries: the Philippines, Malaysia and Indonesia and with the inclusion of include Vietnam and Thailand representation planned. The overarching aims of this project are to:             
-improve the understanding of, and capability to model, large-scale atmospheric processes that influence high impact weather in Southeast Asia;
-evaluate and develop convective scale models to investigate and improve high impact weather forecasts over Southeast Asia; and
-develop tools and processes that improve high impact weather advice, meeting user needs.</narrative>
  </description>
